## Quick Start Template

Create `CLAUDE.md` in your project root:

```markdown
# Project Name

## Project Type
[Brief description: e.g., "React e-commerce SPA with Node.js API"]

## Tech Stack
- Frontend: [React 18, Tailwind CSS, React Router]
- Backend: [Node.js, Express, PostgreSQL]
- [Other key technologies]

## Installed Puerto Plugins
- engineering (agents: frontend-engineer, backend-engineer, data-engineer, devops-engineer, qa-engineer, mobile-engineer, security-engineer)
- design (agents: ux-researcher, ux-writer, accessibility-specialist, visual-designer)
- [List other installed plugins]

## Automatic Task Routing

### Frontend Tasks
WHEN creating React components → AUTOMATICALLY invoke engineering/frontend-engineer
WHEN implementing state management → AUTOMATICALLY invoke engineering/frontend-engineer
WHEN styling components → AUTOMATICALLY invoke engineering/frontend-engineer

### Backend Tasks
WHEN creating API endpoints → AUTOMATICALLY invoke engineering/backend-engineer
WHEN implementing authentication → AUTOMATICALLY invoke engineering/backend-engineer

### [Add sections for other plugins you've installed]

## Project Patterns

### Component Structure
- Components live in: `src/components/`
- Use Tailwind for styling (no CSS modules)
- Follow existing pattern in `src/components/ProductCard.tsx`

### API Conventions
- REST endpoints in: `src/api/routes/`
- Use Zod for request validation
- Follow pattern in `src/api/routes/products.ts`

### [Add other project-specific patterns]

## Domain Knowledge
[Brief business context that helps agents make appropriate decisions]
- [Key business rule 1]
- [Key business rule 2]
```

**Usage**: Copy this template, fill in your project details, and save as `CLAUDE.md` in your project root.

---

## Section-by-Section Breakdown

### 1. Project Type & Tech Stack

**Purpose**: Give Claude immediate context about what type of project this is.

```markdown
## Project Type
Full-stack e-commerce platform with React frontend and Express backend

## Tech Stack
- Frontend: React 18, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS, React Query
- Backend: Node.js 20, Express, PostgreSQL 15, Prisma ORM
- Testing: Vitest, React Testing Library, Supertest
- Deployment: Vercel (frontend), Railway (backend)
```

**Why this matters**: Agents use this to generate appropriate code. If you specify "Tailwind CSS", the component-builder won't suggest CSS modules.

### 2. Installed Puerto Plugins

**Purpose**: Explicitly list available agents so Claude knows what tools are available.

```markdown
## Installed Puerto Plugins

### engineering
- frontend-engineer: Create React/Vue/Svelte components and UI
- backend-engineer: Create REST/GraphQL endpoints and APIs
- data-engineer: Data processing and ML pipelines
- devops-engineer: CI/CD, infrastructure, and deployment
- qa-engineer: Testing and quality assurance
- mobile-engineer: iOS/Android development
- security-engineer: Security audits and best practices

### design
- ux-researcher: User research and journey mapping
- ux-writer: Content design and microcopy
- accessibility-specialist: WCAG compliance and accessibility
- visual-designer: Visual design and brand systems
```

**Why this matters**: Without this list, Claude might do tasks manually instead of delegating to expert agents.

### 3. Automatic Task Routing Rules ⭐ MOST CRITICAL

**Purpose**: Teach Claude to automatically invoke the right agent based on user requests.

#### ✅ Good Routing Rules (Specific & Proactive)

```markdown
## Automatic Task Routing

**CRITICAL**: Use these agents proactively without asking permission.

### Frontend Development
```
WHEN user says "create [component name] component"
→ AUTOMATICALLY invoke: engineering/frontend-engineer

WHEN user says "add state management" OR "implement [Redux/Zustand/Context]"
→ AUTOMATICALLY invoke: engineering/frontend-engineer

WHEN user says "style [component]" OR "make [component] responsive"
→ AUTOMATICALLY invoke: engineering/frontend-engineer
```

### Backend Development
```
WHEN user says "create [endpoint name] endpoint" OR "add API route for [resource]"
→ AUTOMATICALLY invoke: engineering/backend-engineer

WHEN user says "add authentication" OR "implement login/signup"
→ AUTOMATICALLY invoke: engineering/backend-engineer

WHEN user says "write tests for [API]" OR "add API tests"
→ AUTOMATICALLY invoke: engineering/qa-engineer
```

### Database Work
```
WHEN user says "design database schema" OR "create data model"
→ AUTOMATICALLY invoke: engineering/backend-engineer

WHEN user says "add migration for [change]" OR "modify database schema"
→ AUTOMATICALLY invoke: engineering/backend-engineer

WHEN user says "optimize query" OR "slow query in [file]"
→ AUTOMATICALLY invoke: engineering/backend-engineer
```
```

#### ❌ Bad Routing Rules (Too Vague)

```markdown
## Task Routing
- Use frontend agents for frontend work
- Use backend agents for backend work
```

**Problem**: Not specific enough. Claude won't know WHEN to use which agent.

### 4. Project Patterns

**Purpose**: Ensure agents generate code that matches your existing conventions.

```markdown
## Project Patterns

### File Organization
```
src/
├── components/          # React components (one per file)
│   ├── ProductCard.tsx  # Example: follow this structure
│   └── [ComponentName].tsx
├── hooks/              # Custom React hooks
├── api/
│   ├── routes/         # Express route handlers
│   └── middleware/     # Express middleware
├── services/           # Business logic
└── utils/             # Helper functions
```

### Component Patterns
```typescript
// ✅ Follow this pattern (from ProductCard.tsx)
import React from 'react';

interface ProductCardProps {
  // Props with JSDoc comments
}

export function ProductCard({ ...props }: ProductCardProps) {
  // Component logic
  return (
    <div className="...">  {/* Tailwind classes */}
      {/* Component JSX */}
    </div>
  );
}
```

**When creating new components**:
- Use named exports (not default)
- TypeScript interfaces for props
- Tailwind for styling
- Follow existing component structure

### API Patterns
```typescript
// ✅ Follow this pattern (from src/api/routes/products.ts)
import { Router } from 'express';
import { z } from 'zod';
import { validateRequest } from '../middleware/validation';

const router = Router();

// Zod schema for validation
const createProductSchema = z.object({
  name: z.string(),
  price: z.number(),
});

// Route handler with validation
router.post('/products', validateRequest(createProductSchema), async (req, res) => {
  // Handler logic
});

export default router;
```

**When creating new endpoints**:
- Use Zod for request validation
- Async/await for handlers
- Consistent error handling middleware
- Follow REST conventions

### Testing Patterns
```typescript
// ✅ Component tests use React Testing Library
import { render, screen } from '@testing-library/react';
import { ProductCard } from './ProductCard';

describe('ProductCard', () => {
  it('renders product information', () => {
    // Test implementation
  });
});

// ✅ API tests use Supertest
import request from 'supertest';
import app from '../app';

describe('POST /products', () => {
  it('creates a new product', async () => {
    // Test implementation
  });
});
```

### Database Patterns
- Use Prisma ORM for all database access
- Migrations live in: `prisma/migrations/`
- Follow naming convention: `YYYYMMDD_description`
- Always include rollback logic in migrations
```

**Why this matters**: Agents read these patterns and generate code that looks like it was written by your team.

### 5. Domain Knowledge

**Purpose**: Business context that helps agents make domain-appropriate decisions.

```markdown
## Domain Knowledge

### E-commerce Business Rules
- **Products have variants**: Size, color, material (stored as separate SKUs)
- **Pricing calculation**: Base price + variant price + tax (by region)
- **Inventory**: Tracked per variant, not per product
- **Cart lifetime**: 24 hours for guest users, 30 days for authenticated
- **Payment processing**: Stripe for cards, PayPal for alternative payment

### Critical Constraints
- All prices stored in cents (integer) to avoid floating-point errors
- Product images must be optimized (<200KB) before storage
- PII (personally identifiable information) must not be logged
- GDPR compliance required: data deletion within 30 days of request

### Integration Points
- Stripe webhooks handle payment confirmations (see `src/webhooks/stripe.ts`)
- SendGrid for transactional emails (see `src/services/email.ts`)
- Cloudinary for image storage and transformation
```

**Why this matters**: Without this context, an agent might create a pricing system that uses floats (causing rounding errors) or log user emails (violating privacy).

